174":"1174","about 1210":"circa 1210","1218":"1218","Rothesay, Bute, Scotland":"Rothesay, Bute, Schotland","Morven, Argyll, Scotland":"Morven, Argyll, Schotland","Scotland":"Schotland","Isle of Bute, Strathclyde, Scotland":"Bute, Schotland","Bute,  Strathclyde, Scotland":"Bute, Schotland"},"en":{"1190–1210":"1190–1210","1174–1218":"1174–1218","1210–1297":"1210–1297","1168–1210":"1168–1210","1174–1245":"1174–1245","1190":"1190","1245":"1245","1168":"1168","1210":"1210","1297":"1297","1210 ":"1210","1174":"1174","about 1210":"about 1210","1218":"1218","Rothesay, Bute, Scotland":"Rothesay, Bute, Scotland","Morven, Argyll, Scotland":"Morven, Argyll, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland","Isle of Bute, Strathclyde, Scotland":"Bute, Scotland","Bute,  Strathclyde, Scotland":"Bute, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Macrory","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish and northern Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Ruaidhrí</b> ‘son of <i>Ruaidhrí</i>’ (see   Rorie  ), a personal name derived from <i>ruadh</i> ‘red’ + <i>rí</i> ‘king’. There is possible influence from the Old Norse personal names <i>Hróthrekr</i> (see   Roderick  ) and <i>Hróthgeirr</i> (see   Rogers   2), forms of which were used as Anglicized equivalents."],"variants":[{"name":"McCreary","meanings":["Irish (northern): Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Ruidhrí</b>, a variant of <b>Mac Ruaidhrí</b>, ‘son of <i>Ruaidhrí</i>’, a personal name meaning ‘red king’. See also   McCrory  ."]},{"name":"Rorie","meanings":["Scottish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Ruaidhrí</b> ‘son of <i>Ruaidhrí</i>’ (Rory); see   McCrory  ."]},{"name":"McGrory","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Liam.","Scottish and northern Irish: variant of   McCrory  ."]},{"name":"McRorie","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   McCrory  ."]},{"name":"McCrorey","meanings":["Scottish and northern Irish: variant of   McCrory  ."]}]},{"name":"Séamus","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Anglicized spelling of <i>Séamas</i> or <i>Séamus</i>, Irish equivalents of   James .  This is now sometimes used also by parents with no Irish connections."],"variants":[{"name":"James","meanings":["form of the name borne in the New Testament by two of Christ's disciples, James son of Zebedee and James son of Alphaeus. This form comes from Late Latin <i>Iacomus</i>, a variant of <i>Iacobus</i>, Latin form of Greek <i>Iakobos</i>. This is the same name as Old Testament   Jacob   (Hebrew <i>Yaakov</i>), but for many centuries now they have been thought of in the English-speaking world as two distinct names. In Britain, <i>James</i> is a royal name that from the beginning of the 15th century onwards was associated particularly with the Scottish house of Stewart:  James I  of Scotland (  1394–1437 ; ruled  1424–37 ) was a patron of the arts and a noted poet, as well as an energetic ruler.  King James VI  of Scotland (  1566–1625 ; reigned  1567–1625 ) succeeded to the throne of England in  1603 . His grandson,  James II  of England (  1633–1701 ; reigned  1685–8 ) was a Roman Catholic, deposed in  1688  in favour of his Protestant daughter Mary and her husband William of Orange. From then on he, his son (also called James), and his grandson Charles (‘Bonnie Prince Charlie’) made various unsuccessful attempts to recover the English throne. Their supporters were known as Jacobites (from Latin <i>Iacobus</i>), and the name James became for a while particularly associated with Roman Catholicism on the one hand, and Highland opposition to the English government on the other. Nevertheless, it has since become one of the most perennially popular boys' names."]},{"name":"Shamus","meanings":["Anglicized spelling of   Séamus   or   Séamas  , now used fairly infrequently."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Séamus MacSomerled Macrory was born in 1190, in Bute, Scotland, his father, Angus MacBeth, was 11187 and his mother, Helen Ragnvaldsdottir, was 16. He married Ragnhild de L'Isles in 1210, in Scotland. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in 1210, in his hometown, at the age of 20, and was buried in Scotland."},"et":{"1190–1210":"1190–1210","1174–1218":"1174–1218","1210–1297":"1210–1297","1168–1210":"1168–1210","1174–1245":"1174–1245","1190":"1190","1245":"1245","1168":"1168","1210":"1210","1297":"1297","1210 ":"1210","1174":"1174","about 1210":"umbes 1210","1218":"1218","Rothesay, Bute, Scotland":"Rothesay, Bute, Scotland","Morven, Argyll, Scotland":"Morven, Argyll, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland","Isle of Bute, Strathclyde, Scotland":"Bute, Scotland","Bute,  Strathclyde, Scotland":"Bute, Scotland"},"fi":{"1190–1210":"1190–1210","1174–1218":"1174–1218","1210–1297":"1210–1297","1168–1210":"1168–1210","1174–1245":"1174–1245","1190":"1190","1245":"1245","1168":"1168","1210":"1210","1297":"1297","1210 ":"1210","1174":"1174","about 1210":"noin 1210","1218":"1218","Rothesay, Bute, Scotland":"Rothesay, Bute, Scotland","Morven, Argyll, Scotland":"Morven, Argyll, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland","Isle of Bute, Strathclyde, Scotland":"Bute, Scotland","Bute,  Strathclyde, Scotland":"Bute, Scotland"},"fr":{"1190–1210":"1190–1210","1174–1218":"1174–1218","1210–1297":"1210–1297","1168–1210":"1168–1210","1174–1245":"1174–1245","1190":"1190","1245":"1245","1168":"1168","1210":"1210","1297":"1297","1210 ":"1210","1174":"1174","about 1210":"environ 1210","1218":"1218","Rothesay, Bute, Scotland":"Rothesay, Bute, Écosse","Morven, Argyll, Scotland":"Morven, Argyll, Écosse","Scotland":"Écosse","Isle of Bute, Strathclyde, Scotland":"Bute, Écosse","Bute,  Strathclyde, Scotland":"Bute, Écosse","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Séamus MacSomerled Macrory est né en 1190, à Bute, Écosse, son père, Angus MacBeth, avait 11187 ans et sa mère, Helen Ragnvaldsdottir, avait 16 ans. Il a épousé Ragnhild de L'Isles en 1210, à Écosse. Ils ont eu au moins 1